{{update|date=April 2015}} {{Infobox award |name = Feminist Porn Award |current_awards = |image = |image size = |caption = |description = Erotica focused on women and marginalized people<ref name="official"/> |presenter = |country = [[Canada]] |year = 2006<ref name=fpa2006>{{Cite news|issn=1486-8008 |page=WP.3 |last=Agrell |first=Siri |title=X-rated films for red-blooded feminists: New porn caters to female pleasure fantasies |work=[[National Post]] |accessdate=September 9, 2011 |date=June 10, 2006 |url=http://www.canada.com/story.html?id=279d0f37-010e-4a9c-a985-459249ec467a |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110909052609/http://www.canada.com/story.html?id=279d0f37-010e-4a9c-a985-459249ec467a |archivedate=September 9, 2011 |df= }}</ref> |website = {{url|http://www.feministpornawards.com}} }}
The '''Feminist Porn Awards''' ('''FPAs''')<ref name=official>{{cite web|url=http://goodforher.com/feminist_porn_awards |title=Feminist Porn Awards {{!}} Good For Her - Sex Workshops |work=Feminist Porn Awards |publisher=Good for Her |accessdate=November 13, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111108032232/http://www.goodforher.com/feminist_porn_awards |archivedate=November 8, 2011 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> is an annual [[pornographic film|adult film]] [[list of film awards|award]]s ceremony that began in 2006, and was initially organized by the Good for Her [[adult store]] in [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]], Canada.<ref name=fpa2006/> Until 2014, the ceremony was officially known as the '''Good for Her Feminist Porn Awards'''.<ref name="vegasseven">{{cite web|url=http://vegasseven.com/2014/06/04/feminist-porn-enters-mainstream|title=Feminist Porn Enters the Mainstream {{!}} Vegas Seven|work=Vegas Seven|publisher=Wendoh Media|last=Comella|first=Lynn|date=June 14, 2014|accessdate=April 19, 2015}}</ref>
==History== Critiquing portrayals of women's sexuality and masculinity in adult film's was not enough, so Good For Her founded the Feminist Porn Awards to celebrate work that complicates dominant representations of desire, desirability, sexuality and gender.<ref>Osworth, Ali. “You Need Help: The Quest For Awesome Queer Feminist Porn.” Autostraddle, February 22, 2013. https://www.autostraddle.com/you-need-help-the-quest-for-awesome-porn-155575/.</ref> The ceremony was originally conceived of and coordinated by former store manager [[Chanelle Gallant]], and it has been organized by current store manager Alison Lee since 2008.<ref name=bedfellows>Nikko Snyder, [http://briarpatchmagazine.com/articles/view/strange-bedfellows/ Strange bedfellows]. ''[[Briarpatch]]''. March 1, 2008. Retrieved February 11, 2012.</ref><ref name=goodmen>Adam Polaski, [http://goodmenproject.com/good-feed-blog/feminist-porn/ 'Porn with a heart' for a male audience]. [[The Good Men Project]]. April 28, 2011. Retrieved November 13, 2011.</ref><ref name=blogto>Chandra Menard, [http://www.blogto.com/film/2009/04/girls_on_film_the_2009_feminist_porn_awards/ Girls on Film: The 2009 Feminist Porn Awards]. April 21, 2009. Retrieved November 13, 2011.</ref> Both the store and the ceremony are based in [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]], and the ceremony commonly takes place at Berkeley Church.<ref name=blogto/><ref name=shameless>Desirée O, [http://www.shamelessmag.com/blog/2009/03/alison-lee-feminist-porn-awards-pioneer/ Alison Lee: Feminist Porn Awards Pioneer] ''[[Shameless (magazine)|Shameless Magazine]]. March 5, 2009. Retrieved November 13, 2011.</ref> Despite the name of the ceremony, Lee states that the films featured at the awards (as well as the ceremony itself) are meant to appeal to men as well as women.<ref name=goodmen/>
Winners at the FPAs are awarded trophies in the shape of [[butt plug]]s.<ref name="Horn">{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/read/turning-assholes-inside-out-at-the-ninth-annual-feminist-porn-awards|title=I Attended the Ninth Annual Feminist Porn Awards|last=Horn|first=Tina|date=May 4, 2014|work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|accessdate=June 16, 2014}}</ref>
==Criteria== According to the official website,<ref name=official/> [[nomination]]s for an FPA are dependent upon three criteria: #Women and/or traditionally marginalized people were involved in the direction, production and/or conception of the work. #The work depicts genuine pleasure, agency and desire for all performers, especially women and traditionally marginalized people. #The work expands the boundaries of sexual representation on film, challenges stereotypes and presents a vision that sets the content apart from most mainstream pornography. This may include depicting a diversity of desires, types of people, bodies, sexual practices, and/or an anti-racist or anti-oppression framework throughout the production.<ref name=official/>
