{{Infobox orchestra | name = Orchestre philharmonique de Strasbourg (OPS) | image = | caption = | founded = 1855 | concert_hall = Palais de la musique et des congrès 'Pierre Pflimlin ' | principal_conductor = Marko Letonja | website = {{URL|www.philharmonique-strasbourg.com}} }} The '''Orchestre philharmonique de Strasbourg''' (Strasbourg Philharmonic Orchestra) is a French orchestra based in [[Strasbourg]]. It is one of the two permanent orchestras of the [[Opéra national du Rhin]] (the other being the [[Orchestre symphonique de Mulhouse]]). The orchestra's current principal venue is the [[Palais de la musique et des congrès]] 'Pierre Pflimlin ' (PMC Pierre-Pflimlin, or PMC).
The orchestra was founded in 1855. Between 1871 and 1918, and 1940 and 1944, the orchestra had been a [[Germany|German]] one, resulting from conflicts between France and Germany over the [[Alsace]] region. In 1994, the orchestra acquired the official title of ''Orchestre philharmonique de Strasbourg – orchestre national''. The orchestra currently holds 110 permanent musicians.<ref>{{cite web|title=Orchestre philharmonique de Strasbourg - orchestre national|url=http://www.philharmonique-strasbourg.com/biographies/ops_vGB.pdf|publisher=philharmonique-strasbourg.com|accessdate=6 November 2015}}</ref> Composers-in-residence included the French composers [[Jean-Louis Agobet]] and [[Philippe Manoury]], the Finnish composer [[Kaija Saariaho]] and the American composer [[John Corigliano]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Les compositeurs en résidence|url=http://www.philharmonique-strasbourg.com/compositeurs-residence.php|website=philharmonique-strasbourg.com|accessdate=1 November 2015}}</ref>
Past music directors and chief conductors have included [[Hans Pfitzner]], [[Hans Rosbaud]], [[Ernest Bour]], [[Jan Latham-Koenig]], [[Charles Bruck]] and [[Alain Lombard]]. [[Marc Albrecht]] became artistic advisor of the orchestra in 2005, and music director in 2008. Albrecht and the orchestra have recorded commercially for [[PentaTone Classics|PENTATONE]], including orchestral lieder of [[Alban Berg]], and piano concertos by [[Robert Schumann]] and [[Antonín Dvořák]].<ref>{{cite news | author=Andrew Clements | url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/dec/04/schumann-dvorak-piano-concerto | title=Schumann: Piano Concerto; Dvorák: Piano Concerto: Helmchen/Strasbourg PO/Albrecht | work=The Guardian | date=2009-12-04 | accessdate=2009-12-06}}</ref> Albrecht concluded his tenure in 2011. In January 2011, the orchestra announced the appointment of Marko Letonja as its next music director, effective with the 2012-2013 season.<ref>{{cite news | author=Danièle Leonard | url=http://alsace.france3.fr/info/marko-letonja-nouveau-directeur-musical-de-l-ops-66965043.html | title=Marko Letonja, nouveau directeur musical de l'OPS | work=France3 TV (Alsace) | date=2011-01-20 | accessdate=2011-09-10 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331105752/http://alsace.france3.fr/info/marko-letonja-nouveau-directeur-musical-de-l-ops-66965043.html | archivedate=2012-03-31 | df= }}</ref>
==Music directors== [[Image:Symphonie des deux rives - 2006 - Salutations.jpg|right|thumb|480px|The orchestra conducted by Jérôme Pillement at the free open-air concert ''Symphonie des deux rives'' in June 2006.<ref>http://www.philharmonique-strasbourg.com/galerie_photo/programmes2rives/progr2006.pdf{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Programme for 2006 ''Symphonie des deux rives'' concert.</ref>]] * Josef Hasselmans (1855–1871) * [[Franz Stockhausen]] (1871–1907) * [[Hans Pfitzner]] (1907–1915) * [[Otto Klemperer]] (1915–1918) * Hans Pfitzner (1918–1919) * [[Guy Ropartz]] (1919–1929) * [[Paul Paray]] (1929–1940) * [[Hans Rosbaud]] (1940–1945) * [[Paul Bastide]] (1945–1950) * [[Ernest Bour]] (1950–1964) * [[Alceo Galliera]] (1964–1971) * [[Alain Lombard]] (1971–1983) * [[Theodor Guschlbauer]] (1983–1997)<ref>''For conductors from 1855 to 1987:'' Van Boer Jnr, BH, Fast, ML. Strasbourg Philharmonic Orchestra. In: ''Symphony Orchestras of the World'', ed Craven RR. Greenword Press, New York, 1987.</ref> * [[Jan Latham Koenig]] (1997–2003) * [[Marc Albrecht]] (2008–2011) * Marko Letonja (2012-present)
