[[Image:AberdeenBestiaryFolio008vLeopardDetail.jpg|thumb|A pard from the ''[[Aberdeen Bestiary]]'' manuscript.]]
A '''pard''' is a legendary animal that is listed in Medieval [[bestiary|bestiaries]]. They were felines with spotted coats and were extremely fast (reminiscent of a [[cheetah]]). They were believed to mate with [[lion]]s to produce [[leopard]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bestiary.ca/beasts/beast116.htm|title=Pard|accessdate=2008-12-28|work=The Medieval Bestiary}}</ref> They were believed to have white or pale spots. These spots were thought to symbolize sins, as the pard was taken to be a symbol of the Devil.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=94opjX2vfjQC&pg=PA35&lpg=PA35&dq=pard+bestiary&source=bl&ots=tXnJRgYIh_&sig=JOfEq2RMrZgiIT_6ZsrMSIiciXY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjO8e74ovveAhVCWqwKHVzSBdUQ6AEwA3oECAQQAQ#v=onepage&q=pard%20bestiary&f=false|title=Pard|accessdate=2018-11-29|work=Bestiary: Being an English Version of the Bodleian Library}}</ref>
==Etymology== The English noun ''pard'' derives from [[Middle English]] ''parde'', from [[Old French]] via [[Latin]] ''pardus'', from [[Greek language|Greek]] {{lang|grc|πάρδος}} ''párdos'' ("male panther"). The word ''pard'' is probably of [[Iranian languages|Iranian]] origin; akin to [[Sogdian language|Sogdian]] ''purdhank''.<ref>[http://www.thefreedictionary.com/pard ''The Free Dictionary'' - Pard]</ref> and [[Persian language|Persian]] پلنگ ''Palang''.
